01:17:39,520 --> 01:17:45,120
Some of the things that are just
mentioned in the book make my blood boil

1078
01:17:45,240 --> 01:17:51,280
and brings back my hatred, in an intense
way, for white supremacists

1079
01:17:51,400 --> 01:17:56,640
and their unbelievable hatred
for other human beings.

1080
01:17:56,760 --> 01:18:00,040
<i>She echoes the conversations
in the living room,</i>

1081
01:18:00,160 --> 01:18:03,320
<i>which is the most dangerous thing
when you're trying to find</i>

1082
01:18:03,440 --> 01:18:06,480
<i>to create a peaceful society.</i>

1083
01:18:07,520 --> 01:18:09,000
<i>Even us as black people,</i>

1084
01:18:09,120 --> 01:18:12,600
<i>we say things in front of our children
about white people.</i>

1085
01:18:12,720 --> 01:18:14,600
<i>We should be very careful...</i>

1086
01:18:14,720 --> 01:18:18,160
<i>because the children learn
by seeing and repeating.</i>

1087
01:18:19,240 --> 01:18:21,920
When I started this journey
with this book, I thought,

1088
01:18:22,040 --> 01:18:24,520
"There's another loony
from Durban... [chuckles]

1089
01:18:24,640 --> 01:18:31,080
<i>...telling stories about the space and
all aliens and interacting with worlds."</i>

1090
01:18:31,200 --> 01:18:32,600
[dramatic music]

1091
01:18:46,960 --> 01:18:50,880
[John] <i>When I knew that she
had communication with Esage,</i>

1092
01:18:51,000 --> 01:18:57,040
<i>one of the highest respected
African</i> sangomas, <i>an African High Priest,</i>

1093
01:18:57,160 --> 01:19:00,640
<i>who was the custodian
of our language, of our culture,</i>

1094
01:19:00,760 --> 01:19:04,960
<i>of African religion and mythology,
Credo Mutwa,</i>

1095
01:19:05,080 --> 01:19:07,840
<i>I had to take a little bit
of a pause and say,</i>

1096
01:19:07,960 --> 01:19:10,840
<i>"Why would Credo Mutwa believe her?"</i>

1097
01:19:10,960 --> 01:19:14,600
<i>So I had to give it a little bit of, well,
the benefit of the doubt.</i>

1098
01:19:14,720 --> 01:19:16,400
<i>"Let me look into this.</i>

1099
01:19:16,520 --> 01:19:20,520
<i>Let me find out what was it that brought
these two people together."</i>

1100
01:19:20,640 --> 01:19:22,120
[music continues]

1101
01:19:41,080 --> 01:19:45,720
The things she talked about
when she was in Meton,

1102
01:19:45,840 --> 01:19:51,200
where she heard about what will happen
if we neglect the Earth...

1103
01:19:52,040 --> 01:19:54,400
if we abuse the Earth,

1104
01:19:54,520 --> 01:19:59,760
if we continue not understanding
climate change, global warming.

1105
01:19:59,880 --> 01:20:04,040
I mean, we as Africans,
we believe that we have ancestors.

1106
01:20:04,160 --> 01:20:06,200
We have... [speaks isiXhosa]

1107
01:20:06,320 --> 01:20:09,760
Which is the creator
that is responsible for all the nature,

1108
01:20:09,880 --> 01:20:11,840
including the dust and the ants,

1109
01:20:11,960 --> 01:20:13,760
and that we have the ancestors

1110
01:20:13,880 --> 01:20:18,320
that mediate our lives and relationships
with our God, <i>Qamatha...</i>

1111
01:20:18,840 --> 01:20:20,920
that brings us great blessings.

1112
01:20:21,040 --> 01:20:25,920
But, I can't see them. I can't...
I've never known where they are.

1113
01:20:26,040 --> 01:20:28,320
Reading this book made me think,

1114
01:20:28,440 --> 01:20:31,160
"Maybe they're not far
from Meton. [chuckles]

1115
01:20:31,280 --> 01:20:33,160
Maybe they are close there."

1116
01:20:33,280 --> 01:20:36,520
But the thing that really sometimes
makes me feel sad,

1117
01:20:36,640 --> 01:20:41,880
that I feel that what Elizabeth Klarer
represented in that paragraph...

1118
01:20:42,760 --> 01:20:45,600
of the hard copy published in 1979,

1119
01:20:45,720 --> 01:20:50,360
about what <i>she</i> thought
about <i>me</i> as a black person...

1120
01:20:50,960 --> 01:20:54,640
<i>She's not alone,
and I'm afraid it still exist.</i>

1121
01:20:54,760 --> 01:20:57,760
We need to find a language
that's unifying.

1122
01:20:57,880 --> 01:21:01,000
We need to find the language
that promotes reconciliation.

1123
01:21:01,120 --> 01:21:05,400
We need to find a new English
that talks about social cohesion,

1124
01:21:05,520 --> 01:21:07,400
that talks about forgiveness.

1125
01:21:07,520 --> 01:21:08,800
[projector slides clicking]

1126
01:21:21,520 --> 01:21:25,880
Am I offended by what she says?
Damn right, I am!

1127
01:21:26,800 --> 01:21:30,800
Do I hate her for it?
I don't have space in my heart to hate,

1128
01:21:30,920 --> 01:21:33,120
I've got so many important things to do.

1129
01:21:37,120 --> 01:21:38,840
[ominous vibration]

1130
01:23:34,480 --> 01:23:37,280
[Kurt Waldheim] <i>As the Secretary General
of the United Nations,</i>

1131
01:23:37,400 --> 01:23:41,160
<i>an organization of 147 member-states</i>

1132
01:23:41,280 --> 01:23:45,960
<i>who represents almost all of the human
inhabitants of the planet Earth</i>

1133
01:23:46,080 --> 01:23:49,600
<i>I send greetings on behalf
of the people of our planet.</i>

1134
01:23:50,960 --> 01:23:53,520
<i>We step out of our solar system...</i>

1135
01:24:03,160 --> 01:24:07,400
<i>We know full well
that our planet and all its inhabitants</i>

1136
01:24:07,520 --> 01:24:12,680
<i>are but a small part of this immense
universe that surrounds us</i>

1137
01:24:12,800 --> 01:24:17,000
<i>and it is with humility and hope
that we take this step.</i>

1138
01:24:17,480 --> 01:24:19,840
[sounds from the
Voyager Golden Records playing]
